It&#x27;s not even about things moving. Some are completely unable to reason about interfaces. I had this conversation with my mother recently: 
Her: &quot;There&#x27;s an error on my screen, what do I do?&quot; 
Me: &quot;What does the error say?&quot;
Her: &quot;The file name you entered is too long. What do I do?&quot;
Me: &quot;Make the file name shorter&quot;
Her: &quot;It worked!&quot;<p><i>facepalm</i>

Isn&#x27;t it funny how C has so many ways to accomplish the same thing. Why did you use a typedef with a tag?<p><pre><code>  typedef struct {
    int a;
    int b;
  } Foo;

  Foo f = { .a = 1 };</code></pre>

That looks a lot like C to me, which I wouldn&#x27;t call a dynamic language.<p><pre><code>  typedef struct Foo {
    int a;
    int b;
  } Foo;

  Foo f = (Foo) { .a = 1 }; // This will initialize b to zero.</code></pre>
